Now, the thing you ought to
know about this MINI Cooper

00:47.159 --> 00:49.560
is, it is small.

00:49.561 --> 00:52.436
(CAR BEEPING)

00:57.436 --> 01:00.338
I like having a MINI Cooper.

01:00.339 --> 01:02.641
I sort of identify with it.

01:03.641 --> 01:06.410
You know?
It's pretty little.

01:06.411 --> 01:10.048
I feel as if it's proportion...

01:10.049 --> 01:12.216
that we are in proportion,
you know?

01:12.217 --> 01:15.152
Me and my car,
we are sort of...

01:15.153 --> 01:19.694
together,
facing the rest of the world.

01:22.694 --> 01:25.696
(WHIMSICAL MUSIC)

01:36.073 --> 01:39.846
(PEOPLE CHANTING INDISTINCTLY)

01:42.846 --> 01:44.749
Economic fairness is,

01:44.750 --> 01:47.851
"the defining issue of our time,
and what the millions..."

01:47.852 --> 01:52.189
This kind of gaping inequality
gives lie to the promise

01:52.190 --> 01:54.190
that's at the very heart
of America.

01:54.191 --> 01:55.926
There is income inequality
in America.

01:55.927 --> 01:57.193
There always has been,

01:57.194 --> 01:58.829
and hopefully
there always will be.

01:58.830 --> 02:01.399
If inequality is at a very
much higher level, who cares?

02:01.400 --> 02:02.466
Income inequality
has been ticking up.

02:02.467 --> 02:03.934
Income inequality is bull.

02:03.935 --> 02:05.235
I think it's about envy.

02:05.236 --> 02:06.904
I think it's about
class warfare.

02:06.905 --> 02:08.906
It's class warfare,
and it's the kind of language

02:08.907 --> 02:10.240
that you would expect

02:10.241 --> 02:11.609
from a leader
of a third world country,

02:11.610 --> 02:13.977
not the president
of the United States.

02:13.978 --> 02:17.447
It's true, because
United States of America

02:17.448 --> 02:20.650
is not a third world country
by any measure,

02:20.651 --> 02:25.288
except perhaps
income inequality,

02:25.289 --> 02:26.323
where we rank...

02:26.324 --> 02:27.358
(BABBLING)

02:27.359 --> 02:28.959
worse than the Ivory Coast,

02:28.960 --> 02:30.126
worse than Cameroon...

02:30.127 --> 02:31.595
64th!

02:31.596 --> 02:36.067
Ah, in your face,
Uruguay, Jamaica, and Uganda!

02:36.068 --> 02:37.100
Yeah.

02:37.101 --> 02:40.002
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

02:40.003 --> 02:43.007
(DOWNTRODDEN JAZZY MUSIC)

03:08.366 --> 03:11.773
(PEOPLE CHATTING INDISTINCTLY)

03:14.773 --> 03:19.075
Okay, are we all here?

03:19.076 --> 03:21.578
My name is Robert Reich.

03:21.579 --> 03:24.413
I was secretary of labor
under Bill Clinton.

03:24.414 --> 03:27.717
Before that, I was at Harvard.

03:27.718 --> 03:30.687
Before that, I was in
the Carter administration.

03:30.688 --> 03:32.156
Do you remember...
does anybody...

03:32.157 --> 03:34.156
You don't remember
the Carter administration.

03:34.157 --> 03:35.359
(LAUGHTER)

03:35.360 --> 03:38.362
Before that,
I was a special aide

03:38.363 --> 03:40.297
to Abraham Lincoln.

03:40.298 --> 03:42.332
(LAUGHTER)

03:42.333 --> 03:45.339
Those were tough times.

03:47.339 --> 03:51.507
We are going to deal
with three questions.

03:51.508 --> 03:55.812
The first question is,
what is happening

03:55.813 --> 04:00.216
in terms of the distribution
of income and wealth?

04:00.217 --> 04:02.787
Number two, why?

04:02.788 --> 04:05.589
Number three, is it a problem?

04:05.590 --> 04:08.726
Maybe it's not a problem.

04:08.727 --> 04:10.995
Many of you call yourselves
conservatives.

04:10.996 --> 04:13.363
Many of you call yourselves
liberals.

04:13.364 --> 04:16.833
Those labels will become
increasingly irrelevant

04:16.834 --> 04:20.971
as you get deeper and deeper
into this subject.

04:20.973 --> 04:25.775
I want you to test
your assumptions.

04:25.776 --> 04:29.679
If possible, I want to shake
your assumptions a little bit

04:29.680 --> 04:35.333
about why the system
works as it does.

04:48.333 --> 04:50.505
Some inequality is inevitable.

04:53.505 --> 04:55.472
If people are gonna have
the proper incentives

04:55.473 --> 04:59.478
to be productive, to work
hard, to be inventive...

05:01.478 --> 05:03.080
that's the essence
of capitalism,

05:03.081 --> 05:07.154
and capitalism does generate
a lot of good things.

05:09.154 --> 05:13.123
Look, the question
is not inequality per se.

05:13.124 --> 05:17.528
The question is, when does
inequality become a problem?

05:17.529 --> 05:21.165
How much inequality
can we tolerate

05:21.166 --> 05:23.900
and still have an economy
that's working for everyone

05:23.901 --> 05:27.703
and still have a democracy
that's functioning?

05:27.704 --> 05:31.909
Of all developed nations
today, the United States has

05:31.910 --> 05:36.580
the most unequal distribution
of income and wealth by far.

05:36.581 --> 05:41.552
And we're surging toward
even greater inequality.

05:41.553 --> 05:43.854
One way of looking at
and measuring inequality

05:43.855 --> 05:46.556
is to look at the earnings
of people at the top

05:46.557 --> 05:47.825
versus the earnings

05:47.826 --> 05:49.562
of the typical worker
in the middle.

05:51.562 --> 05:54.564
The typical male worker in 1978

05:54.565 --> 05:58.802
was making around $48,000,
adjusted for inflation,

05:58.803 --> 06:01.470
while the average person
in the top 1%

06:01.471 --> 06:04.874
earned $390,000.

06:04.875 --> 06:06.410
Now fast-forward.

06:06.411 --> 06:09.547
By 2010,
the typical male worker

06:09.548 --> 06:11.681
earned even less
than he did then,

06:11.682 --> 06:13.350
but the person at the top

06:13.351 --> 06:16.822
got more than twice as much
as before.

06:17.822 --> 06:21.525
Today the richest 400
Americans have more wealth

06:21.526 --> 06:25.729
than the bottom 150 million
of us put together.

06:25.730 --> 06:26.797
Now, think about it.

06:26.798 --> 06:29.732
400 people have more wealth

06:29.733 --> 06:34.203
than half the population
of the United States.

06:34.204 --> 06:36.373
(PEOPLE CHANTING INDISTINCTLY)

06:36.374 --> 06:39.042
Anger rising over an
economic system

06:39.043 --> 06:40.376
that has rewarded some

06:40.377 --> 06:44.080
but leaves many
feeling left behind.

06:44.081 --> 06:46.616
After the economy crashed
in 2008,

06:46.617 --> 06:49.753
inequality suddenly
became front-page news.

06:49.754 --> 06:52.189
Who else wants to join the 1%?

06:52.190 --> 06:53.523
You look like a one percenter.

06:53.524 --> 06:55.292
We're a fabulous percent.

06:55.293 --> 06:59.330
People from both parties were
looking for someone to blame.

06:59.331 --> 07:02.265
But most people have no idea
how it got this bad

07:02.266 --> 07:03.406
or why.

07:09.406 --> 07:10.974
Not until the last few years

07:10.975 --> 07:14.410
have we really understood
all that much about inequality.

07:14.411 --> 07:17.780
I mean,
we knew the top 10% or 20%

07:17.781 --> 07:19.249
were moving in one direction

07:19.250 --> 07:21.886
and the bottom 10% or 20%
was moving in another.

07:21.887 --> 07:24.621
But we didn't know what was
happening at the very top,

07:24.622 --> 07:27.224
to the top 1%.

07:27.225 --> 07:28.958
Hello.
How are you doing?

07:28.959 --> 07:30.059
Good to see you.

07:30.060 --> 07:32.462
And then a few years ago,
two researchers,

07:32.463 --> 07:34.797
Emmanuel Saez
and Thomas Piketty,

07:34.798 --> 07:36.737
found a different
source of data.

07:38.737 --> 07:42.004
They looked at IRS tax data,

07:42.005 --> 07:44.340
not just
over the last few years

07:44.341 --> 07:48.011
but all the way back to 1913,

07:48.012 --> 07:51.584
when the income tax
was instituted.

07:53.584 --> 07:56.487
It showed that there
were two peak years.

07:56.488 --> 08:01.290
1928 and 2007
become the peak years

08:01.291 --> 08:03.126
for income concentration,

08:03.127 --> 08:05.595
both of them in which the
top 1% is taking home

08:05.596 --> 08:08.668
more than 23% of total income.

08:10.668 --> 08:13.537
We knew that inequality
had started to increase

08:13.538 --> 08:16.006
in the late '70s and the 1980s,

08:16.007 --> 08:20.210
but we didn't know
how dramatically

08:20.211 --> 08:21.910
income concentration
had increased,

08:21.911 --> 08:24.147
especially within the top 1%.

08:24.148 --> 08:27.650
When you had this study
come out in 2003,

08:27.651 --> 08:29.753
it sat there
for a number of years,

08:29.754 --> 08:34.023
and then suddenly
it became important.

08:34.024 --> 08:36.427
But you see them
starting to recover...

08:36.428 --> 08:38.796
This graph becomes very central

08:38.797 --> 08:42.131
for explaining what has
happened to the U.S. economy

08:42.133 --> 08:46.635
and, indeed, what's happening
and has happened to our society.

08:46.636 --> 08:49.908
It looks like
a suspension bridge.

08:50.908 --> 08:53.476
What happened
the year after 1928?

08:53.477 --> 08:54.710
The Great Crash.

08:54.711 --> 08:57.279
And what happened
just after 2007?

08:57.280 --> 08:58.317
Another crash.

09:00.317 --> 09:03.552
The parallels are breathtaking

09:03.553 --> 09:06.156
if you look at them carefully.

09:06.157 --> 09:09.158
(BOLD BRASS MUSIC)

09:13.697 --> 09:16.298
Leading up to those
two peak years,

09:16.299 --> 09:18.701
as income got more and
more concentrated

09:18.702 --> 09:20.903
in fewer and fewer hands,

09:20.904 --> 09:23.373
the wealthy turned
to the financial sector,

09:23.374 --> 09:27.845
and in both periods, the
financial sector ballooned.

09:27.846 --> 09:30.580
They focused on a limited
number of assets:

09:30.581 --> 09:34.118
housing, gold,
speculative instruments,

09:34.119 --> 09:36.487
debt instruments.

09:36.488 --> 09:38.321
And that creates
a speculative bubble

09:38.322 --> 09:40.257
in both times.

09:40.258 --> 09:42.725
We also know
that the middle class,

09:42.726 --> 09:46.129
in both periods, their
incomes were stagnating,

09:46.130 --> 09:48.264
and they went deeper
and deeper into debt

09:48.265 --> 09:50.933
to maintain
their living standards.

09:50.934 --> 09:52.238
And that creates a debt bubble.

09:54.238 --> 09:55.239
(BUBBLE POPS)

09:55.240 --> 09:56.473
(CHILD SCREAMING)

09:56.474 --> 09:58.874
That's why you see,
in both these periods,

09:58.875 --> 10:02.144
economic instability.

10:02.145 --> 10:06.917
What makes an economy stable
is a strong middle class.

10:06.918 --> 10:10.620
Look, the most important
thing to understand

10:10.621 --> 10:13.790
is that consumer spending
is 70%

10:13.791 --> 10:16.759
of the United States economy.

10:16.760 --> 10:19.461
And the middle class
is the heart

10:19.462 --> 10:23.133
of that consumer spending.

10:23.134 --> 10:27.738
So it's your middle class
that keeps the economy going.

10:27.739 --> 10:31.041
There's no way you can sustain
the economy over the long term

10:31.042 --> 10:35.778
without a strong and vibrant
and growing middle class.

10:35.779 --> 10:36.417
Can't be done.

10:39.417 --> 10:41.151
People are being intimidated.
Correct.

10:41.152 --> 10:42.985
I mean, they might
lose their jobs if they...

10:42.986 --> 10:45.721
I talk to a lot
of different groups.

10:45.722 --> 10:49.292
Some are wealthy.
Some are working-class.

10:49.293 --> 10:51.128
Some are conservative.
Some are liberal.

10:51.129 --> 10:55.231
And he finally got
a full-time job.

10:55.232 --> 10:57.267
The middle class is struggling.

10:57.268 --> 10:59.668
It is going downhill.

10:59.669 --> 11:01.904
I hear it all the time.

11:01.905 --> 11:03.473
Well, everyone tells me
that I am,

11:03.474 --> 11:05.908
but I don't feel
like I'm middle-class,

11:05.909 --> 11:07.344
because I'm barely making it.

11:07.345 --> 11:10.346
Middle-class
is living comfortably

11:10.347 --> 11:13.950
and not having to... not having
every week be a struggle.

11:13.951 --> 11:16.185
I'd like to save up
and buy a house one day,

11:16.186 --> 11:18.455
and, you know, I haven't
really been able to do that

11:18.456 --> 11:20.791
and been kind of holding back

11:20.792 --> 11:23.529
and just trying to make rent
right now.

11:25.529 --> 11:29.932
How much do you make an hour?

11:29.933 --> 11:34.303
Right now,
I think it went up... $21.50.

11:34.304 --> 11:36.672
$21.50 an hour.

11:36.673 --> 11:38.541
<i>Hola, Alberto.</i>

11:38.542 --> 11:40.442
I think I'm being paid fair.

11:40.443 --> 11:43.112
It got to a point
that we were able to afford,

11:43.113 --> 11:48.284
you know, a condo
on Olivera Road,

11:48.285 --> 11:50.086
and we bought it.

11:50.087 --> 11:52.723
We had our own things,
our own place.

11:52.724 --> 11:55.796
It was little,
you know, two-bedroom.

11:58.796 --> 12:02.999
We bought it in 2004.

12:03.000 --> 12:07.604
Around 2006, start of 2007,

12:07.605 --> 12:09.939
the market just dropped
like a rock.

12:09.940 --> 12:13.009
And not that long after,
actually,

12:13.010 --> 12:17.547
I lost my job that I'd been at
for a long time.

12:17.548 --> 12:20.048
Luckily we had
some really good friends,

12:20.049 --> 12:21.750
and one of them said,

12:21.751 --> 12:24.521
"Come over here
and live with me."

12:24.522 --> 12:27.393
So that's where we are now.

12:28.393 --> 12:29.692
Go with Daddy.

12:29.693 --> 12:31.561
Go with Daddy.
I'm hungry.

12:31.562 --> 12:34.330
You're hungry?

12:34.331 --> 12:39.869
Child care for Paulina right now
costs me about $400.

12:39.870 --> 12:43.907
I'm, like, undecided whether
I should make her walk home...

12:43.908 --> 12:45.542
buy her a phone and walk home,

12:45.543 --> 12:47.610
making sure she gets home okay,

12:47.611 --> 12:49.612
or keep paying a day care.

12:49.613 --> 12:52.485
Bye.
Here, Mom.

12:54.485 --> 12:55.125
Ready?

13:01.125 --> 13:04.460
I have $25 in my
checking account right now

13:04.461 --> 13:08.031
and just thinking about
all the things that we need.

13:08.032 --> 13:09.532
I don't have a way
of communicating

13:09.533 --> 13:11.100
with Robert right now.

13:11.101 --> 13:14.003
He doesn't have a phone,
so we have to wait for that.

13:14.004 --> 13:15.872
I got to figure out...
we have to have enough,

13:15.873 --> 13:19.947
you know, food on the
table for the kids.

13:22.947 --> 13:24.848
$25 in your checking account,

13:24.849 --> 13:27.617
that's got to be...

13:27.618 --> 13:29.552
That's not very much.

13:29.553 --> 13:31.553
No, it's not.

13:31.554 --> 13:33.023
(SNIFFLES)

13:33.024 --> 13:35.591
But, I mean, it's Tues...
it's Wednesday.

13:35.592 --> 13:37.859
I'll survive today.

13:37.860 --> 13:39.061
I'll look up in the pantry,

13:39.062 --> 13:41.663
see what else is there to eat.

13:41.664 --> 13:44.968
I have a full tank of gas,
so I'm fine on that part.

13:44.969 --> 13:47.009
I don't need to go anywhere
right now.

13:53.009 --> 13:54.778
When I was laid off,
I decided to go ahead

13:54.779 --> 13:57.714
and pursue my degree
at that point.

13:57.715 --> 14:02.485
Most of the classmates I have
are a lot younger than I am.

14:02.486 --> 14:04.354
It's different
when you're reading about it

14:04.355 --> 14:06.422
or somebody else's issues.

14:06.423 --> 14:08.891
That's different from when
it's your own family's.

14:08.892 --> 14:10.159
So when it hits home,

14:10.160 --> 14:12.629
that's probably
the hardest part.

14:12.630 --> 14:17.100
There is no official definition
of the middle class.

14:17.101 --> 14:18.468
But Alan Krueger,

14:18.469 --> 14:20.403
chairman of the Council
of Economic Advisors,

14:20.404 --> 14:22.104
these are the percentage
of households

14:22.105 --> 14:27.643
with annual incomes within 50%
of the median household.

14:27.644 --> 14:32.285
$50,000, median income,
50% above, 50% below.

14:35.285 --> 14:37.653
If you're in the top %1,
you're earning

14:37.654 --> 14:40.790
at least $380,000 a year.

14:40.791 --> 14:42.892
If you're at the lower end
of this group,

14:42.893 --> 14:44.528
you're probably
at the top levels

14:44.529 --> 14:47.997
of the professional fields,
a top doctor or a top lawyer.

14:47.998 --> 14:49.298
Higher in this group,

14:49.299 --> 14:50.933
earning several million
dollars a year,

14:50.934 --> 14:54.403
are successful entrepreneurs
who start profitable companies.

14:54.404 --> 14:58.474
At the highest levels, earning
$10 million a year or more,

14:58.475 --> 15:00.743
are the CEOs of big companies,

15:00.744 --> 15:04.080
the heads of Wall Street
banks, top entertainers,

15:04.081 --> 15:06.883
and also the top sports stars.

15:06.884 --> 15:12.021
Last year, we made $36,000,
and we're a family of three.

15:12.022 --> 15:13.290
I think I probably make

15:13.291 --> 15:15.358
in between $45,000
and $50,000 a year

15:15.359 --> 15:19.129
working 70 hours a week,
six days a week.

15:19.130 --> 15:20.696
Combined income with the army

15:20.697 --> 15:27.070
and with my personal job,
maybe $55,000 to $60,000 a year.

15:27.071 --> 15:32.841
Probably close to $600,000.

15:32.842 --> 15:36.778
Usually more than $10 million,
less than $30 million

15:36.779 --> 15:38.148
but, you know, a lot,

15:38.149 --> 15:41.221
a ridiculous amount of money.

15:44.221 --> 15:46.755
I am an entrepreneur
and venture capitalist.

15:46.756 --> 15:49.959
My family owns a large
manufacturer of bed pillows

15:49.960 --> 15:52.394
and down comforters called
Pacific Coast Feather Company.

15:52.395 --> 15:54.297
We are, in fact,
one the largest manufacturers

15:54.298 --> 15:56.375
of those things in the world.

16:05.375 --> 16:08.311
The problem
with rising inequality is,

16:08.312 --> 16:11.080
a person like me,
who earns 1,000 times as much

16:11.081 --> 16:13.649
as the typical American,

16:13.650 --> 16:16.418
doesn't buy 1,000 pillows
a year.

16:16.419 --> 16:20.293
Even the richest people only
sleep on one or two pillows.

16:22.293 --> 16:24.393
The pillow business
is quite tough,

16:24.394 --> 16:27.196
as it is for many,
many industries,

16:27.197 --> 16:31.367
because fewer and fewer
people can afford to buy

16:31.368 --> 16:34.206
the products that we make.

16:36.206 --> 16:38.543
(CAR ALARM CHIRPS)

16:40.543 --> 16:42.311
And I have the nicest
Audi you can get,

16:42.312 --> 16:45.281
but it's still only one Audi.

16:45.282 --> 16:47.517
I personally hate fancy food.

16:47.518 --> 16:50.653
I would infinitely rather
go have a great bowl

16:50.654 --> 16:52.721
of pho at the local
Vietnamese place

16:52.722 --> 16:57.130
than a five-course $300
dinner at some fancy place.

16:59.130 --> 17:00.763
You know, we can only
go out to eat

17:00.764 --> 17:02.331
so many times a year.

17:02.332 --> 17:04.633
We can only get
so many haircuts a year.

17:04.634 --> 17:07.604
We can only get...
I can, you know...

17:07.605 --> 17:09.471
Three pairs of jeans
will do you, you know?

17:09.472 --> 17:11.175
Like, you don't need 300 pairs.

17:13.175 --> 17:15.178
The problem isn't that the rich

17:15.179 --> 17:17.046
spend too much
of what they earn.

17:17.047 --> 17:20.349
It's actually, paradoxically,
that they spend too little.

17:20.351 --> 17:23.154
They're not generating
enough economic activity.

17:25.154 --> 17:27.390
Somebody earning
$10 million a year

17:27.391 --> 17:30.293
doesn't spend $10 million.

17:30.294 --> 17:31.826
They save it.

17:31.827 --> 17:34.797
And those savings go
anywhere around the world.

17:34.798 --> 17:39.135
They can make the most money,
get the highest return.

17:39.136 --> 17:42.838
They become part
of the global capital market,

17:42.839 --> 17:45.274
including a lot
of speculative instruments,

17:45.275 --> 17:48.178
having gold and real estate
and anything else

17:48.179 --> 17:50.747
that they're all chasing.

17:50.748 --> 17:55.317
With the exception of the
money I personally invest

17:55.318 --> 17:59.221
to start companies,
I have essentially no idea

17:59.222 --> 18:00.990
what happens to my money.

18:00.991 --> 18:03.993
I invest in funds of funds,

18:03.994 --> 18:08.097
and those hedge funds
do God knows what with it.

18:08.098 --> 18:10.700
But I do believe absolutely

18:10.701 --> 18:13.702
that most of the return
that's being created

18:13.703 --> 18:17.073
isn't creating
any kind of social utility

18:17.074 --> 18:20.175
other than creating
a return for me.

18:20.176 --> 18:22.178
Now, ordinarily we like saving.

18:22.179 --> 18:24.046
I mean, savings are good,
but when we have

18:24.047 --> 18:27.683
so much unemployment,
so much underutilized capacity

18:27.684 --> 18:31.822
here in the United States,
we need spending.

18:31.823 --> 18:37.259
Every single person there has
to process 12 units per hour.

18:37.260 --> 18:39.496
How are we gonna create jobs
if you're taxing

18:39.497 --> 18:41.698
the very successful people
in America

18:41.699 --> 18:43.399
who provide those jobs?

18:43.400 --> 18:46.568
Sometimes we think
that this is a debate

18:46.569 --> 18:48.970
over facts and figures
and data.

18:48.971 --> 18:52.409
To raise taxes on the job
creators in this country...

18:52.410 --> 18:53.709
I think if you believe that,

18:53.710 --> 18:55.444
you're fooling yourself
a little bit.

18:55.445 --> 18:58.448
The people that you call rich,
I call job creators.

18:58.449 --> 19:00.783
When somebody calls
themselves a job creator,

19:00.784 --> 19:03.419
they're not describing
the economy

19:03.420 --> 19:04.787
or how the economy works,

19:04.788 --> 19:06.722
although that's
what it sounds like.

19:06.723 --> 19:09.592
What they're really doing
is making a claim

19:09.593 --> 19:13.364
on status, privileges,
and power.

19:14.364 --> 19:16.731
If a guy like me
is a job creator

19:16.732 --> 19:18.800
at the center
of the economic universe,

19:18.801 --> 19:21.971
the current
economic arrangements

19:21.972 --> 19:25.208
are righteous and justified.

19:25.209 --> 19:26.976
I know how comfortable
this is to believe

19:26.977 --> 19:29.545
because I used to believe it.

19:29.546 --> 19:31.914
You know, I grew up
kind of believing that.

19:31.915 --> 19:34.316
You know, and when people
challenged that idea,

19:34.317 --> 19:35.751
I would say things like,

19:35.752 --> 19:37.886
"Well, you just don't
understand economics."

19:37.887 --> 19:39.889
(LAUGHS)

19:39.890 --> 19:42.659
But of course,
if rich business guys like me

19:42.660 --> 19:44.960
are not job creators...
it's actually our customers

19:44.961 --> 19:46.496
that are the job creators...

19:46.497 --> 19:49.265
we are not the center
of the economic universe.

19:49.266 --> 19:50.536
They are.

19:52.536 --> 19:56.338
We need to replace
trickle-down economics

19:56.339 --> 19:58.741
with middle-out economics.

19:58.742 --> 20:02.644
And, indeed,
every place you look on Earth

20:02.645 --> 20:06.548
where you find prosperity,
you finds massive investments

20:06.549 --> 20:08.317
in the middle class
and the poor,

20:08.318 --> 20:12.854
because at the end of the day,
they are the true job creators.

20:12.855 --> 20:15.758
The most pro-business thing
you can do

20:15.759 --> 20:19.394
is to help middle-class
people thrive.

20:50.394 --> 20:53.395
Okay, I'm gonna get the box.

20:53.396 --> 20:57.633
Now, see, this box
is really important.

20:57.634 --> 20:59.935
I travel not only
with my MINI Cooper

20:59.936 --> 21:01.903
but with my box.

21:01.904 --> 21:04.207
(HUMMING)

21:04.208 --> 21:05.608
Hello, George.
How are you?

21:05.609 --> 21:07.143
You are so kind
to bring the box.

21:07.144 --> 21:08.510
We have one for you too.

21:08.511 --> 21:09.745
It's the same room and...

21:09.746 --> 21:11.047
In recent years,
I've discovered

21:11.048 --> 21:14.217
that I actually have
a very, very rare

21:14.218 --> 21:16.585
genetic condition.

21:16.586 --> 21:18.854
It's Fairbanks Syndrome

21:18.855 --> 21:22.324
that is responsible
for me being very short.

21:22.325 --> 21:25.393
Hey, Bob, let me carry that.
No, no, no, that's fine.

21:25.394 --> 21:27.630
My parents were normal size.

21:27.631 --> 21:29.732
My grandmother
always said to me,

21:29.733 --> 21:31.367
"Don't worry,"
'cause when I hit

21:31.368 --> 21:34.738
about 10 or 11 or 12,
I'm gonna,

21:34.739 --> 21:37.573
you know,
have a real growth spurt.

21:37.574 --> 21:39.541
And then I got to be
about 10, 11,

21:39.542 --> 21:41.576
and nothing happened, you know?

21:41.577 --> 21:42.945
Right up this way to the right.

21:42.946 --> 21:43.979
Right this way.

21:43.980 --> 21:45.413
Yup, behind you.

21:45.414 --> 21:48.765
(APPLAUSE)

22:01.765 --> 22:04.467
I grew up in the shadow
of World War II.

22:04.468 --> 22:08.136
My father was in the war.

22:08.137 --> 22:10.105
We were middle-class.

22:10.106 --> 22:13.144
My father sold dresses.
My mother helped in the shop.

22:15.144 --> 22:19.147
My first job in Washington
was working as a summer intern

22:19.148 --> 22:22.719
for Robert Kennedy.

22:22.720 --> 22:25.454
It was a time when there
were kind of giants.

22:25.455 --> 22:28.391
Robert F. Kennedy,
Martin Luther King,

22:28.392 --> 22:31.559
they were all
trying to change society.

22:31.560 --> 22:33.997
There was a sense
of possibility.

22:33.998 --> 22:37.232
It kind of turned me on
to politics.

22:37.233 --> 22:40.635
A few years later, I was
picked to be a Rhodes Scholar.

22:40.636 --> 22:42.904
In those days,
all the Rhodes Scholars

22:42.905 --> 22:45.946
who were selected
took a boat to England.

22:50.946 --> 22:53.582
The problem was, you know,
when you go over there,

22:53.583 --> 22:57.120
the Atlantic Ocean
is pretty rough.

22:57.121 --> 23:00.021
You know, I and most
of the other Rhodes Scholars

23:00.022 --> 23:02.892
were sick,
and I went down to my cabin.

23:02.893 --> 23:04.531
You know,
I thought I was gonna die.

23:08.531 --> 23:10.665
And then there was a knock
on the door,

23:10.666 --> 23:12.701
and this fellow was there,

23:12.702 --> 23:15.004
this kind of tall,
gangly Southerner,

23:15.005 --> 23:17.306
and he had chicken soup
in one hand

23:17.307 --> 23:19.374
and crackers in the other,

23:19.375 --> 23:21.743
and he said, "I hear
you aren't feeling too well.

23:21.744 --> 23:23.278
"I thought these might help.

23:23.279 --> 23:26.149
My name is Bill Clinton."

23:26.150 --> 23:28.550
At Oxford,
we were at the same college.

23:28.551 --> 23:30.556
We kept in touch.

23:32.556 --> 23:34.958
At Oxford,
I studied mostly economics

23:34.959 --> 23:37.326
and philosophy.

23:37.327 --> 23:40.595
But those experiences
really were a study for me

23:40.596 --> 23:43.232
of the rules by which
markets are organized.

23:43.233 --> 23:44.767
And this is an important point,

23:44.768 --> 23:47.903
and it's one
that's very often lost,

23:47.904 --> 23:51.339
but it was the focus
of my attention.

23:51.340 --> 23:52.608
You see, there's no such thing

23:52.609 --> 23:55.044
as a perfectly free market
anywhere.

23:55.045 --> 24:00.016
Government sets the rules
by which the market functions.

24:00.017 --> 24:02.885
All of these rules
are necessary

24:02.886 --> 24:06.889
in order to construct
a free market.

24:06.890 --> 24:10.526
The real question is,
who do these rules benefit

24:10.527 --> 24:12.760
and who do they hurt?

24:12.761 --> 24:15.130
And in the last 30 years,

24:15.131 --> 24:18.201
as the structure of the
economy began to shift,

24:18.202 --> 24:20.769
many of the rules
governing our market

24:20.770 --> 24:23.009
began to shift as well.

24:26.009 --> 24:28.411
Today we're going
to try to explain

24:28.412 --> 24:34.616
the mystery of why inequality
has been widening.

24:34.617 --> 24:37.586
Remember, the economy is
growing all of this time.

24:37.587 --> 24:38.787
The economy is...

24:38.788 --> 24:40.789
The economy continues to grow.

24:40.790 --> 24:43.258
Look, here is
gross domestic product growth

24:43.259 --> 24:46.261
from 1929 to 2011.

24:46.262 --> 24:49.565
The economy overall
has done extremely well,

24:49.566 --> 24:51.933
and productivity
keeps on increasing.

24:51.934 --> 24:54.269
We are producing
more and more and more

24:54.270 --> 24:55.738
and more and more value.

24:55.739 --> 24:58.007
That's a big, big
success story.

24:58.008 --> 25:00.041
But here is the problem.
Here's the puzzle.

25:00.042 --> 25:02.845
Because if you look at the
average hourly earnings

25:02.846 --> 25:04.614
of production workers,

25:04.615 --> 25:09.050
the average hourly earning
continued to rise

25:09.051 --> 25:15.191
until the late 1970s,
and then something happened,

25:15.192 --> 25:17.693
flattening wages.

25:17.694 --> 25:20.596
Look at the gap.

25:20.597 --> 25:24.200
Something happened
in the late 1970s.

25:24.201 --> 25:29.771
Something happened
in the late 1970s, folks.

25:29.772 --> 25:32.976
(FUNKY MUSIC)

25:38.548 --> 25:40.516
In the late 1970s,

25:40.517 --> 25:43.251
I was at the Federal
Trade Commission.

25:43.252 --> 25:45.453
I was looking at
a lot of studies

25:45.454 --> 25:50.191
about the direction that
the economy was going in.

25:50.192 --> 25:53.796
More of American manufacturing
was beginning to move abroad.

25:53.797 --> 25:59.133
There was the beginnings
of a technological revolution.

25:59.134 --> 26:03.105
Financial markets were becoming
a little bit more powerful.

26:03.106 --> 26:05.844
There was a move to deregulate.

26:07.844 --> 26:10.479
Well, you connect the dots,
and all of these

26:10.480 --> 26:14.851
begin to look as if
they're connected somehow

26:14.852 --> 26:17.624
to this widening inequality.

26:20.624 --> 26:24.727
For example, we knew that
labor unions were declining.

26:24.728 --> 26:27.864
And that decline mirrored
almost exactly

26:27.865 --> 26:29.931
the decline
in the middle class' share

26:29.932 --> 26:32.401
of national income.

26:32.402 --> 26:34.103
(PEOPLE CHANTING INDISTINCTLY)

26:34.104 --> 26:36.038
The hard part is stepping back

26:36.039 --> 26:38.806
and seeing the big picture.

26:38.807 --> 26:40.875
Many people, even to this day,

26:40.876 --> 26:44.614
say that the decline of unions
really was attributable

26:44.615 --> 26:49.352
to Ronald Reagan taking on
the air traffic controllers.

26:49.353 --> 26:51.688
ALL: Strike, strike, strike,
strike, strike, strike...

26:51.689 --> 26:55.391
I must tell those who failed
to report for duty this morning,

26:55.392 --> 27:00.262
they have forfeited their
jobs and will be terminated.

27:00.263 --> 27:03.499
There's no question that
beginning in the late '70s

27:03.500 --> 27:07.769
but also after Reagan fired
the air traffic controllers,

27:07.770 --> 27:14.277
there was a major assault
on unions.

27:14.278 --> 27:18.181
Employers did try to prevent
unions from being formed

27:18.182 --> 27:20.382
much more aggressively
than before...

27:20.383 --> 27:22.986
I'll go.
You don't have to hang on to me.

27:22.987 --> 27:26.322
And employers fought
to bust unions

27:26.323 --> 27:27.856
that were already there.

27:27.857 --> 27:30.093
(PEOPLE CLAMORING)

27:30.094 --> 27:34.029
But maybe they were doing so
because they felt they had to

27:34.030 --> 27:37.600
in order to maintain
their competitiveness

27:37.601 --> 27:44.006
given so many other companies
that were nonunion

27:44.007 --> 27:48.678
in the United States and
also many companies abroad.

27:48.679 --> 27:56.679
The major underlying issue
was two interrelated things:

27:57.054 --> 28:01.323
globalization and technology.

28:01.324 --> 28:03.191
I mean, you hear the word
"globalization"

28:03.192 --> 28:04.893
over and over and over again.

28:04.894 --> 28:07.630
Globalization, globalization,
globalization.

28:07.631 --> 28:09.966
Rarely has a word gone
so directly

28:09.967 --> 28:14.335
from obscurity
to meaninglessness

28:14.336 --> 28:17.105
without any intervening
period of coherence.

28:17.106 --> 28:18.373
(LAUGHTER)

28:18.374 --> 28:21.777
Can anybody lend me
their iPhone for a moment?

28:21.778 --> 28:24.645
Anybody have one that...
great.

28:24.646 --> 28:26.515
Thank you.

28:26.516 --> 28:27.883
I don't have one,

28:27.884 --> 28:30.518
and I've really wanted
to have one.

28:30.519 --> 28:33.055
(LAUGHTER)

28:33.056 --> 28:37.727
Where do most of your dollars go
when you buy an iPhone?

28:37.728 --> 28:39.228
What do you think?

28:39.229 --> 28:41.930
Let's go.
Let's do the bidding.

28:41.931 --> 28:44.333
A little over 700 of you
have these clickers,

28:44.334 --> 28:47.170
which is great.

28:47.171 --> 28:49.137
You say mostly
to the United States,

28:49.138 --> 28:51.206
some of you say to China,

28:51.207 --> 28:56.679
and then some of you say...
a few of you say Japan.

28:56.680 --> 28:58.779
11 of you think Germany.

28:58.780 --> 29:01.986
(LAUGHTER)

29:02.986 --> 29:07.456
Well, here is where
your dollars go.

29:07.457 --> 29:10.526
Most of your dollars
are going to Japan.

29:10.527 --> 29:13.295
Some of your dollars
are going to Germany.

29:13.296 --> 29:15.130
In fact, Germany
is the biggest...

29:15.131 --> 29:16.397
is the second-biggest one.

29:16.398 --> 29:18.432
South Korea's the third,
and here,

29:18.433 --> 29:20.568
6% of your dollars are going
to the United States,

29:20.569 --> 29:24.574
and only 3.6% of your dollars
are going to China.

29:24.575 --> 29:27.576
Now, it's assembled in China.

29:27.577 --> 29:28.710
Do you get this?

29:28.711 --> 29:30.278
It's assembled in China,

29:30.279 --> 29:34.083
but the assembly is of pieces

29:34.084 --> 29:35.851
from all over the place.

29:35.852 --> 29:38.692
Everything is coming
from everywhere.

29:43.692 --> 29:46.729
I wanted my students to see
it's not just

29:46.730 --> 29:48.329
cost of wages or labor.

29:48.330 --> 29:52.170
It's also which country's
workers add what value.

29:54.170 --> 29:58.073
My MINI Cooper
is made by a foreign company.

29:58.074 --> 30:00.276
But where a company's
headquartered

30:00.277 --> 30:02.413
means less and less
in this new global economy.

30:04.413 --> 30:07.950
Technologies
like cargo ships, containers,

30:07.951 --> 30:10.419
satellite communication
technologies,

30:10.420 --> 30:13.154
and eventually
computers and the internet,

30:13.155 --> 30:16.893
these technologies enabled
the production process

30:16.894 --> 30:20.162
to be parceled out
around the world.

30:20.163 --> 30:22.831
Large numbers of American
manufacturing workers

30:22.832 --> 30:25.701
began to lose their jobs,

30:25.702 --> 30:29.136
which meant it inevitably
began undercutting

30:29.137 --> 30:33.010
the wages of a lot
of working Americans.

30:35.010 --> 30:37.312
Even factories remaining
in the United States

30:37.313 --> 30:40.787
shed workers as they automated.

30:43.787 --> 30:45.954
And we have this romantic idea

30:45.955 --> 30:48.022
that we can get
manufacturing back.

30:48.023 --> 30:50.124
But you get manufacturing
plants back,

30:50.125 --> 30:52.126
and they're filled
with robots and computers.

30:52.127 --> 30:54.697
The old assembly line is gone.

30:54.698 --> 30:58.768
I was one of the earliest
investors in amazon.com.

30:58.769 --> 31:02.904
I consider amazon.com
to be one of the greatest

31:02.905 --> 31:05.106
economic achievements
of our time

31:05.107 --> 31:08.778
and certainly something
I'm incredibly proud of.

31:08.779 --> 31:15.616
But make no mistake:
amazon.com employs 60,000 people

31:15.617 --> 31:20.489
and does $70 billion,
$80 billion in sales.

31:20.490 --> 31:22.624
But if mom-and-pop retailers
were doing

31:22.625 --> 31:26.027
that $70 billion or
$80 billion in sales,

31:26.028 --> 31:28.497
it would be 60,000 people
employed doing it.

31:28.498 --> 31:32.567
It'd be 600,000 or 800,000
or a million people

31:32.568 --> 31:38.172
because those business models
are so much less efficient.

31:38.173 --> 31:41.710
So Amazon created
a huge economic windfall

31:41.711 --> 31:43.711
here in the Pacific Northwest,

31:43.712 --> 31:45.914
but all over the country,

31:45.915 --> 31:48.150
there are people
who are no longer employed

31:48.151 --> 31:51.890
in selling stuff
who are not happy.

31:53.890 --> 31:55.624
As a manager for Circuit City,

31:55.625 --> 31:59.361
it was a look behind
the curtain, so to speak,

31:59.362 --> 32:03.531
as a manager, to see exactly
how everything worked.

32:03.532 --> 32:05.901
So when you got laid off,
did you see it coming,

32:05.902 --> 32:07.536
or was it sudden?

32:07.537 --> 32:11.106
They did several layoffs
while I was there.

32:11.107 --> 32:12.908
People who had been there too long:

32:12.909 --> 32:14.677
"They're making too much money

32:14.678 --> 32:16.577
"because they've
been there too long,

32:16.578 --> 32:21.450
and we're gonna have to do
something to cut the payroll."

32:21.451 --> 32:25.491
The hardest part was thinking,
"Is it gonna happen to me?"

32:29.491 --> 32:31.360
Until I became a student,
it was pretty dicey.

32:31.361 --> 32:32.894
I mean, it would have been
easy for me

32:32.895 --> 32:34.997
to just fall into depression,

32:34.998 --> 32:36.499
which happens
to a lot of people,

32:36.500 --> 32:39.067
or go for a lower-paying job,
which would have

32:39.068 --> 32:43.074
put me in a worse
financial situation.

32:45.074 --> 32:49.678
Looking back on it,
you can see the pattern.

32:49.679 --> 32:52.014
It's not as easy to see
when you're in it,

32:52.015 --> 32:53.481
but the signs were there.

32:53.482 --> 32:58.720
I mean, there was
a major slowdown in business,

32:58.721 --> 33:00.556
and I think a lot of that
had to do

33:00.557 --> 33:03.758
with things like Amazon.

33:03.759 --> 33:06.961
Because I've been in retail
for so long,

33:06.962 --> 33:10.198
I don't go through
the automated checkout lines.

33:10.199 --> 33:12.366
And one of the main reasons
is because I know

33:12.367 --> 33:14.269
that every time
I go through that,

33:14.270 --> 33:17.974
it's taking a little bit
of someone's job away.

33:18.974 --> 33:21.308
It's not that I think
that I'm going to...

33:21.309 --> 33:23.746
save their jobs
in the long run.

33:23.747 --> 33:25.448
But I know
that I'm gonna slow down

33:25.449 --> 33:28.717
the transition a little bit
so that maybe

33:28.718 --> 33:31.252
they're gonna have
a little bit longer

33:31.253 --> 33:33.127
to get ready for the transition.

33:39.127 --> 33:41.096
Contrary to popular mythology,

33:41.097 --> 33:44.100
globalization and technology
haven't really

33:44.101 --> 33:46.701
reduced the number of jobs
available to Americans.

33:46.702 --> 33:51.586
These transformations
have reduced their pay.

34:02.586 --> 34:05.187
I mean, it's not just
that wages are stagnating,

34:05.188 --> 34:07.655
but when you take
into consideration

34:07.656 --> 34:09.391
rising costs...

34:09.393 --> 34:13.129
the rising costs of rents
or homes,

34:13.130 --> 34:16.297
dramatically increasing costs
of health care,

34:16.297 --> 34:18.667
the rising costs of child care,

34:18.668 --> 34:21.569
and also the rising costs
or higher education,

34:21.570 --> 34:24.605
rising much faster
than inflation...

34:24.606 --> 34:27.141
Take all of these
into consideration,

34:27.143 --> 34:28.509
and you find
that it's much worse

34:28.510 --> 34:30.645
than just stagnating wages.

34:30.646 --> 34:33.882
It's basically
middle-class families,

34:33.884 --> 34:35.484
often with two wage earners,

34:35.485 --> 34:38.020
working harder and harder
and harder

34:38.021 --> 34:40.393
and getting nowhere.

34:43.393 --> 34:49.031
I work at a law firm
as a litigation assistant.

34:49.032 --> 34:50.899
And Moises?

34:50.900 --> 34:54.402
I work as a bus operator.

34:54.404 --> 34:57.573
Do you know how much is in
your bank account right now?

34:57.574 --> 34:59.475
Mine is less than 100 bucks.

34:59.476 --> 35:02.576
So I want to say maybe $80.

35:02.577 --> 35:05.080
Yeah, yesterday
it was only $30.

35:05.081 --> 35:07.015
(LAUGHTER)

35:07.016 --> 35:08.183
And that's with us working.

35:08.184 --> 35:09.484
Yeah.

35:09.485 --> 35:11.220
Car insurance, $125.

35:11.221 --> 35:13.221
Kids' World, $150.

35:13.222 --> 35:15.758
Rent, $1,375.

35:15.759 --> 35:18.259
We felt like we had
to write it all down,

35:18.260 --> 35:20.662
because how could we
not have money?

35:20.663 --> 35:21.562
We make money.

35:21.563 --> 35:23.332
You know, I'm working now.

35:23.333 --> 35:26.067
We don't know how much we're
gonna be paying on that.

35:26.068 --> 35:27.502
The Y.

35:27.503 --> 35:29.171
This is my money that I donate.

35:29.172 --> 35:32.306
$16 a month
to Children International.

35:32.307 --> 35:36.578
We don't even have here
my UCSF bill.

35:36.579 --> 35:38.647
Remember that hospital bill?

35:38.648 --> 35:40.348
It's, like,
200 and something dollars

35:40.349 --> 35:42.017
that's not even here
that we need to pay.

35:42.018 --> 35:43.317
Oh, yeah.

35:43.318 --> 35:45.654
What about savings?

35:45.655 --> 35:47.122
We haven't been able to.

35:47.123 --> 35:49.723
We don't have
a savings account.

35:49.724 --> 35:53.528
I took it off because it...
It wasn't working.

35:53.529 --> 35:54.562
(LAUGHS)

35:54.563 --> 35:57.433
Oh, you brought your glove.

35:57.434 --> 35:59.100
Did you guys play baseball?

35:59.101 --> 36:01.035
And she's been playing with you?

36:01.036 --> 36:02.971
When she was born,
we had no money.

36:02.972 --> 36:05.841
The refrigerator was empty.
The freezer was empty.

36:05.842 --> 36:08.009
I said, "This is not the way
I want to raise my daughter."

36:08.010 --> 36:10.812
How was your day?
Good.

36:10.813 --> 36:14.549
I've seen single mothers
work three jobs

36:14.550 --> 36:18.252
just to be able to pay rent.

36:18.253 --> 36:20.020
And I didn't want that.

36:20.021 --> 36:21.527
So I started going to school.

36:24.527 --> 36:27.495
How do you build wealth?

36:27.496 --> 36:29.263
Not that I want to be wealthy.

36:29.264 --> 36:30.265
I just...

36:30.266 --> 36:31.834
How do you do it?

36:31.835 --> 36:33.401
How the heck
do you build wealth,

36:33.402 --> 36:35.203
like, when you don't
have anything,

36:35.204 --> 36:38.439
when you don't have any assets,
when you don't have nothing?

36:38.440 --> 36:41.310
This is gonna be Mommy's office.
Look.

36:41.311 --> 36:43.312
This is gonna be my office.

36:43.313 --> 36:44.812
It's not my office yet,

36:44.813 --> 36:47.915
but it's going to be
my office really soon.

36:47.916 --> 36:49.218
Hmm?

36:49.219 --> 36:50.785
People, I think,
would be less concerned

36:50.786 --> 36:53.455
about inequality
of income and wealth

36:53.456 --> 36:56.692
if everybody had a chance
to make it.

36:56.693 --> 36:58.493
As long as there's
upward mobility,

36:58.494 --> 37:01.796
as long as anybody
with enough guts and gumption

37:01.797 --> 37:04.332
and hard work
can make it in America,

37:04.333 --> 37:09.605
can move up the income ladder,
then we don't have a problem.

37:09.606 --> 37:12.908
But as income inequality rises,

37:12.909 --> 37:16.712
upward mobility is actually
less than it was before.

37:16.713 --> 37:18.245
Come on.
You want to see the rest?

37:18.246 --> 37:20.547
Yeah.

37:20.548 --> 37:24.419
In the United States,
42% of kids born into poverty

37:24.420 --> 37:26.154
will not get out.

37:26.155 --> 37:27.723
Compare that to Denmark,

37:27.724 --> 37:31.794
where only 25% of kids
born into poverty stay there.

37:31.795 --> 37:33.160
Even Great Britain,

37:33.161 --> 37:35.796
a country that still has
an aristocracy,

37:35.797 --> 37:38.503
has more upward mobility
than we do.

37:40.503 --> 37:43.471
You know, people
occasionally say to me,

37:43.472 --> 37:47.642
"Okay, Reich, if you think
it can be done better,

37:47.643 --> 37:49.944
"what nation does it better?

37:49.945 --> 37:52.446
Whom should we emulate?"

37:52.447 --> 37:55.417
And the answer is

37:55.418 --> 37:56.389
the United States.

38:01.389 --> 38:04.459
In the three decades
after World War II,

38:04.460 --> 38:07.062
a period that I call
"the Great Prosperity,"

38:07.063 --> 38:08.997
the economy boomed,

38:08.998 --> 38:11.033
but not only
did the economy boom,

38:11.034 --> 38:14.472
but you had very low inequality.

38:16.472 --> 38:19.306
We made education
a national priority,

38:19.307 --> 38:22.776
particularly higher education.

38:22.777 --> 38:26.147
By 1940,
only 5% of adult Americans

38:26.148 --> 38:27.982
had a four-year college degree,

38:27.983 --> 38:31.289
but that percentage
began to explode.

38:34.289 --> 38:36.225
The GI Bill paid college costs

38:36.226 --> 38:37.792
for those who returned
from war,

38:37.793 --> 38:40.796
and the subsequent expansion
of public universities

38:40.797 --> 38:44.899
made higher education
affordable to many.

38:44.900 --> 38:49.038
By the late '50s, we had
the best-educated workforce

38:49.039 --> 38:51.073
of any country in the world.

38:51.074 --> 38:52.306
(GAVEL POUNDING)

38:52.307 --> 38:54.679
We also had labor unions.

38:56.679 --> 39:00.381
By the mid-1950s,
more than 1/3 of all workers

39:00.382 --> 39:02.917
belonged to a union.

39:02.918 --> 39:05.421
This gave average workers
bargaining leverage

39:05.422 --> 39:08.689
to get a larger share
of the growing pie.

39:08.690 --> 39:11.292
We created
the largest middle class

39:11.293 --> 39:12.826
the world had ever seen.

39:12.827 --> 39:17.487
And that middle class
was part of a virtuous cycle.

39:38.487 --> 39:40.254
The wider their prosperity,

39:40.255 --> 39:42.957
the more people were included
in that prosperity,

39:42.958 --> 39:45.137
the more that prosperity
generated more prosperity.

39:54.137 --> 39:55.541
Hello.

39:59.541 --> 40:03.278
Okay, now,

40:03.279 --> 40:07.716
they're gonna be calling in
momentarily.

40:07.717 --> 40:09.616
From American Public Media,

40:09.617 --> 40:12.319
this is <i> Marketplace.</i>

40:12.320 --> 40:16.725
(UPBEAT PERCUSSIVE MUSIC)

40:16.726 --> 40:18.560
America's already
making it harder

40:18.561 --> 40:21.163
for young people of modest
means to attend college.

40:21.164 --> 40:24.598
41 states are cutting spending
for public higher education,

40:24.599 --> 40:27.806
and tuition and fees
are rising as a result.

40:30.806 --> 40:32.839
One of the things we've
learned about inequality

40:32.840 --> 40:35.776
is that it's clearly
linked to education,

40:35.777 --> 40:39.214
including higher education.

40:39.215 --> 40:41.883
More than anything else,
that's what lifted people

40:41.884 --> 40:43.685
out of poverty
and into the middle class

40:43.686 --> 40:45.854
during the Great Prosperity.

40:45.855 --> 40:48.089
But starting in the late 1970s,

40:48.090 --> 40:51.197
our college graduation rates
began to flatten out.

40:55.197 --> 40:58.033
Countries that kept focusing
on higher education

40:58.034 --> 41:00.767
were able to deal
with globalization better

41:00.768 --> 41:03.937
by creating
a highly skilled workforce.

41:03.938 --> 41:06.040
Look at South Korea.
Look at the Netherlands.

41:06.041 --> 41:08.343
Look at Germany.

41:08.344 --> 41:11.212
They've invested
substantially in education,

41:11.213 --> 41:15.582
in skill building
of all of their workers.

41:15.583 --> 41:17.017
Even though their wages
are high,

41:17.018 --> 41:18.752
it's worth it to make stuff

41:18.753 --> 41:21.156
that goes into the iPhone
from Germany

41:21.157 --> 41:25.627
because it is so well made
and is so precise.

41:25.628 --> 41:27.761
Basically, every other
industrialized country...

41:27.762 --> 41:30.966
Japan, Germany, France...
they are investing per capita

41:30.967 --> 41:34.335
much more public investment
in all of the areas:

41:34.336 --> 41:36.571
roads, bridges,
public education.

41:36.572 --> 41:37.671
That's what we're not doing.

41:37.672 --> 41:38.872
That's what we have to be doing.

41:38.873 --> 41:40.207
We're almost out of time.

41:40.208 --> 41:41.676
We can't do it,
not with new tech.

41:41.677 --> 41:43.310
For years, I have been writing

41:43.311 --> 41:45.680
about the importance
of investing in people,

41:45.681 --> 41:48.383
in our workforce, so that
our people could compete

41:48.384 --> 41:50.954
in this new global economy.

41:51.954 --> 41:55.589
And then in 1992,
I thought I finally

41:55.590 --> 41:57.991
might be able
to do something about it.

41:57.992 --> 42:01.029
Today I proudly announce
my candidacy

42:01.030 --> 42:03.665
for president of the
United States of America.

42:03.666 --> 42:05.933
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

42:05.934 --> 42:09.404
Bill Clinton told me
he had read all my books.

42:09.405 --> 42:10.904
They must have influenced him,

42:10.905 --> 42:14.676
because it formed the
backbone of his 1992 campaign

42:14.677 --> 42:16.977
about putting people first.

42:16.978 --> 42:19.046
If you put people first,
if you do what works,

42:19.047 --> 42:21.316
what we know works
in the global economy,

42:21.317 --> 42:23.919
you'll do what the Germans do;
you'll do what the Japanese do.

42:23.920 --> 42:25.053
You'll put your people first.

42:25.054 --> 42:26.955
You'll expand the middle class.

42:26.956 --> 42:29.357
I mean, here was, you know,
somebody I'd known

42:29.358 --> 42:32.493
from the age of 22,
and he called me one day

42:32.494 --> 42:35.663
and said, "Look, Bob,
what I really want you to do

42:35.664 --> 42:37.799
"is come down to Washington
right now.

42:37.800 --> 42:41.468
I need you to run the
economic transition team."

42:41.469 --> 42:44.476
I didn't even know what an
economic transition team was.

42:48.476 --> 42:52.881
You can't imagine the
headiness, the excitement.

42:52.882 --> 42:56.618
I mean, the chance
to actually take these ideas,

42:56.619 --> 42:59.220
put them into practice...

42:59.221 --> 43:02.756
I named my economic plan
Putting People First

43:02.757 --> 43:04.759
to highlight my belief
that our nation

43:04.760 --> 43:08.196
can only become a high-wage,
high-growth economy

43:08.197 --> 43:11.700
if we make a commitment to
invest in the American people

43:11.701 --> 43:14.535
to make the American economy
prosper.

43:14.536 --> 43:18.506
That is why I'm naming today
one of my most trusted advisors

43:18.507 --> 43:20.008
and closest friends

43:20.009 --> 43:22.047
to the position
of secretary of labor.

43:25.047 --> 43:28.216
Well, modesty aside,
I have assumed for months

43:28.217 --> 43:31.051
that I was on Bill Clinton's
short list.

43:31.052 --> 43:32.986
You can step up on that, Bob.
There is a step.

43:32.987 --> 43:35.524
Oh, there is a step here.
Okay.

43:35.525 --> 43:37.459
It was a dream job

43:37.460 --> 43:40.794
for somebody like me,
who had worried about

43:40.795 --> 43:43.631
and fretted about
and studied and taught about

43:43.632 --> 43:45.600
and wrote about
what was happening

43:45.601 --> 43:48.102
to the American workforce
for years.

43:48.103 --> 43:51.038
That long decline
in median wages...

43:51.039 --> 43:52.841
the wage of that person
smack in the middle

43:52.842 --> 43:55.776
of the wage scale...
that decline started in 1978.

43:55.777 --> 43:57.278
Those wages began to decline

43:57.279 --> 43:59.379
in terms of the real purchasing
power of the dollar...

43:59.380 --> 44:01.850
You know, on the one side,
it was pretty clear

44:01.851 --> 44:05.854
that wages were flat
for most people.

44:05.855 --> 44:08.489
The flip side was that
some people in this country

44:08.490 --> 44:10.032
were doing extraordinarily well.

44:17.032 --> 44:19.232
You see,
the same new technologies

44:19.233 --> 44:21.870
that brought globalization
and automation

44:21.871 --> 44:24.738
bestowed ever larger rewards
on people

44:24.739 --> 44:27.642
who had the right education
and connections

44:27.643 --> 44:29.347
to take advantage
of globalization.

44:32.347 --> 44:34.549
Some people say to me,
"But wait a minute.

44:34.550 --> 44:37.986
You've got technologies today
that you didn't have in 1980."

44:37.987 --> 44:40.254
You know, we didn't have
flat-screen televisions.

44:40.255 --> 44:42.522
We didn't have
low-cost air travel.

44:42.523 --> 44:44.225
We didn't have Skype.

44:44.226 --> 44:47.127
We didn't have the internet.

44:47.128 --> 44:49.062
So who are
the winners and losers

44:49.063 --> 44:52.634
from this great shift?

44:52.635 --> 44:54.868
Consumers certainly are winning.

44:54.869 --> 44:57.538
I mean, you guys, as consumers,

44:57.539 --> 44:58.874
you are doing very well.

44:58.875 --> 45:01.207
You get wonderful products.

45:01.208 --> 45:05.212
Almost everything you're
buying is getting cheaper,

45:05.213 --> 45:08.216
and the investors
are doing well.

45:08.217 --> 45:12.687
Here is a chart showing
the rise and fall

45:12.688 --> 45:14.723
of the Dow Jones
Industrial Average.

45:14.724 --> 45:17.459
You can see something here.

45:17.460 --> 45:19.326
There is sort of a pattern.

45:19.327 --> 45:20.361
Whoo!

45:20.362 --> 45:21.562
(LAUGHTER)

45:21.563 --> 45:24.198
You see, something happened,

45:24.199 --> 45:28.803
and I think it happened
starting right in these years.

45:28.804 --> 45:31.839
(LAUGHTER)

45:31.840 --> 45:34.975
You see these were the...

45:34.976 --> 45:37.779
years I was labor secretary.

45:37.780 --> 45:40.647
And investors got very excited.

45:40.648 --> 45:42.584
(LAUGHTER)

45:42.585 --> 45:43.817
I mean, we all saw

45:43.818 --> 45:45.986
the stock market
going like this.

45:45.987 --> 45:47.022
I mean, how...

45:47.023 --> 45:48.489
What in the world was going on?

45:48.490 --> 45:49.957
How could that be possible?

45:49.958 --> 45:53.463
Were companies suddenly
that much more profitable?

45:55.463 --> 45:57.297
One of the big reasons
corporations

45:57.298 --> 46:02.069
were showing higher profits is,
they were keeping pay down.

46:02.070 --> 46:04.437
At the same time,
corporate CEOs

46:04.438 --> 46:07.308
were starting to pay
themselves large multiples

46:07.309 --> 46:09.544
of what the average worker
was earning.

46:09.545 --> 46:12.113
When we, in the fourth
quarter of last year,

46:12.114 --> 46:13.913
along with a number
of other companies,

46:13.914 --> 46:16.984
has to consider
workforce reductions,

46:16.985 --> 46:18.953
it was a difficult time.

46:18.954 --> 46:22.357
You knew that you
were impacting people

46:22.358 --> 46:25.426
who would have a difficult
time, many of them,

46:25.427 --> 46:27.995
in finding new jobs,
but you had to do it

46:27.996 --> 46:34.804
for the organization to,
in that day, look to survive.

46:35.804 --> 46:39.006
This chart shows you
the compensation

46:39.007 --> 46:43.444
of the highest-paid
executives in 2010.

46:43.445 --> 46:46.948
These executives are being
paid a lot of money.

46:46.949 --> 46:50.116
Executive pay keeps going up.

46:50.117 --> 46:53.254
Here's the ratio
of average CEO compensation

46:53.255 --> 46:55.122
to the average worker's pay.

46:55.123 --> 47:00.294
Suddenly this ratio
goes kablooey.

47:00.295 --> 47:04.966
Bill Clinton in 1992,
one of his campaign planks

47:04.967 --> 47:07.435
was that no company
should be able

47:07.436 --> 47:10.171
to deduct the cost
of executive compensation

47:10.172 --> 47:11.772
in excess of $1 million.

47:11.773 --> 47:15.042
Many big corporate executives
raised their own salaries

47:15.043 --> 47:17.243
even when their companies
were losing money

47:17.244 --> 47:20.848
and their workers were being put
into the unemployment lines.

47:20.849 --> 47:23.283
I expect the jet-setters
and the featherbedders

47:23.284 --> 47:26.254
of corporate America to know
that if you sell your companies

47:26.255 --> 47:28.221
and your workers and your
country down the river,

47:28.222 --> 47:29.890
you'll be called on the carpet.

47:29.891 --> 47:33.026
That's what the president's
bully pulpit is for.

47:33.027 --> 47:34.595
When it came
to actually implementing it,

47:34.596 --> 47:38.332
the Treasury Department decided
that as long as CEO pay

47:38.333 --> 47:40.868
was linked
to company performance,

47:40.869 --> 47:43.504
you could deduct pay
over $1 million.

47:43.505 --> 47:47.341
Well, that was the signal
to a lot of executives

47:47.342 --> 47:51.412
and to their boards of directors
to make more and more

47:51.413 --> 47:54.316
of executive pay
into stock options.

47:54.317 --> 47:57.218
That's where the whole
stock option thing came from.

47:57.219 --> 48:00.221
It was kind of a perversion
of Bill Clinton's promise

48:00.222 --> 48:02.559
in the 1992 election.

48:04.559 --> 48:06.694
Another result of all of this
is that you get

48:06.695 --> 48:11.431
the third group of people who
are doing remarkably well.

48:11.432 --> 48:13.535
They're the people
who always do well,

48:13.536 --> 48:16.604
particularly in times
of high inequality:

48:16.605 --> 48:17.872
the financiers.

48:17.873 --> 48:20.808
(PEOPLE CLAMORING)

48:20.809 --> 48:23.611
Between 1997 and 2007,

48:23.612 --> 48:27.582
finance was the fastest-growing
part of the American economy.

48:27.583 --> 48:30.651
In 2009, during the depths
of the recession,

48:30.652 --> 48:34.654
the seven highest-paid
hedge fund managers

48:34.655 --> 48:37.927
were taking in
more than $1 billion each.

48:39.927 --> 48:42.363
Remember that government
sets the rules

48:42.364 --> 48:44.737
by which the market functions.

48:47.737 --> 48:50.171
We deregulated Wall Street,

48:50.172 --> 48:52.306
allowing Wall Street to engage

48:52.307 --> 48:55.047
in more and more excessive
behavior.

48:59.047 --> 49:01.482
These are
the financial sector wages

49:01.483 --> 49:03.219
relative to everyone else's.

49:05.219 --> 49:07.520
Does this graph look familiar?

49:07.521 --> 49:09.957
I mean, this is
our bridge graph,

49:09.958 --> 49:11.859
our old inequality graph.

49:11.860 --> 49:13.331
It's the same pattern.

49:15.331 --> 49:18.133
And meanwhile you've got
many working people

49:18.134 --> 49:21.067
succumbing to this huge lie

49:21.068 --> 49:25.439
that government is bad,
that the market is good,

49:25.440 --> 49:29.243
that everything government
does works against you

49:29.244 --> 49:31.178
and everything the
market does helps you.

49:31.179 --> 49:33.413
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

49:33.414 --> 49:35.517
Our Father in heaven,
we thank You for this food

49:35.518 --> 49:36.951
that's been placed before us.

49:36.952 --> 49:38.419
We ask You to bless it.

49:38.420 --> 49:39.754
Bless the hands
that prepared it.

49:39.755 --> 49:41.254
Bless it'll strengthen
our bodies.

49:41.255 --> 49:42.957
We ask a special blessing
this day, Lord,

49:42.958 --> 49:44.225
for those that have no food.

49:44.226 --> 49:46.426
Bless them
with comfort and hope.

49:46.427 --> 49:47.261
Amen.

49:47.262 --> 49:50.131
Ooh, ooh.
This looks good.

49:50.132 --> 49:53.067
I am registered
as a Republican.

49:53.068 --> 49:55.502
It probably has to do
with our religion too,

49:55.503 --> 49:56.837
okay, Mormons.

49:56.838 --> 49:58.305
The majority
of the Mormons are.

49:58.306 --> 50:00.441
There are those rare Democrats,

50:00.442 --> 50:02.276
but the majority of them
are Republicans.

50:02.277 --> 50:04.477
Oh, I called them,
but you know what it is?

50:04.478 --> 50:06.546
I don't look at myself
as someone

50:06.547 --> 50:08.281
that's economically troubled.

50:08.282 --> 50:10.884
No way.
But I am worried about my kids.

50:10.885 --> 50:15.790
We have paid for doctor bills.
We've paid for dental bills.

50:15.791 --> 50:18.692
Two of my children right now
do not have health insurance.

50:18.693 --> 50:22.196
Our kids without health care
was a big turning point for us.

50:22.197 --> 50:24.034
That really got my attention.

50:26.034 --> 50:29.470
I'm a power plant operator.

50:29.471 --> 50:31.105
Where I work, The Geysers,

50:31.106 --> 50:34.008
it's a renewable energy source.

50:34.009 --> 50:35.776
Calpine is a good company.

50:35.777 --> 50:37.812
They are.

50:37.813 --> 50:39.814
So then why are they
cutting back on people

50:39.815 --> 50:41.281
and cutting sick leave?

50:41.282 --> 50:44.551
Well, the operation
will be more profitable

50:44.552 --> 50:47.687
if they cut back on personnel.

50:47.688 --> 50:49.960
That's a given.

50:52.960 --> 50:56.932
(PEOPLE CHATTING INDISTINCTLY)

50:57.932 --> 51:02.303
I've always been pro-union
from a philosophical standpoint.

51:02.304 --> 51:05.205
I consider myself
part of the labor force.

51:05.206 --> 51:08.711
Therefore I think labor
needs a say.

51:10.711 --> 51:13.781
The company brought in
anti-union consultants

51:13.782 --> 51:18.252
and put on a good campaign
to counter the union.

51:18.253 --> 51:20.754
Let me just say I came here...

51:20.755 --> 51:22.656
Some of you were still
on the fence.

51:22.657 --> 51:23.558
Some people walked out.

51:23.559 --> 51:25.959
There was tension in the air.

51:25.960 --> 51:28.162
The underlying reality

51:28.163 --> 51:29.997
is that if workers
don't have power,

51:29.998 --> 51:32.066
if they don't have a voice,

51:32.067 --> 51:36.437
inevitably their wages
and benefits start eroding.

51:36.438 --> 51:38.872
It happens inevitably.

51:38.873 --> 51:41.109
Personally
I'm a proud Christian.

51:41.110 --> 51:43.276
I'm a proud Calpine employee.

51:43.277 --> 51:46.013
I think they treat me more fair

51:46.014 --> 51:47.582
than I should be treated.

51:47.583 --> 51:52.419
If you have a company that is
dependent on shareholders,

51:52.420 --> 51:56.056
there is growing and growing
pressure on that company

51:56.057 --> 51:57.457
to show better
and better profits

51:57.458 --> 51:59.259
and have higher and higher
share prices.

51:59.260 --> 52:00.960
That's just
the way capitalism is.

52:00.961 --> 52:02.162
That's not bad.

52:02.163 --> 52:04.864
But what that means inevitably

52:04.865 --> 52:07.533
is that there's greater
and greater pressure

52:07.534 --> 52:12.105
to push wages and benefits
down to the minimum.

52:12.106 --> 52:14.308
So you're a capitalist.
I'm a capitalist.

52:14.309 --> 52:16.243
I say for these people
making their millions,

52:16.244 --> 52:17.678
that's fantastic.

52:17.679 --> 52:19.413
I could have done
the same thing

52:19.414 --> 52:21.415
if I went to school
and had the brains for it.

52:21.416 --> 52:22.750
I do not.
(LAUGHS)

52:22.751 --> 52:24.218
So I'm a laborer.

52:24.219 --> 52:25.785
And there's such a burden
on the companies

52:25.786 --> 52:29.189
in the United States now
that the cost of business

52:29.190 --> 52:32.459
drives that...
them to go elsewhere.

52:32.460 --> 52:33.727
But this right now

52:33.728 --> 52:35.562
is the richest country
in the world,

52:35.563 --> 52:37.631
and we are richer
than we've ever been.

52:37.632 --> 52:40.734
Believe me, we as a
nation are doing great,

52:40.735 --> 52:42.535
and certain people
in this country

52:42.536 --> 52:45.473
are doing better than anybody
has ever done in the world

52:45.474 --> 52:47.508
in world history.

52:47.509 --> 52:49.276
(PEOPLE CHATTING INDISTINCTLY)

52:49.277 --> 52:50.845
It's not just Calpine.

52:50.846 --> 52:54.482
I took a $12-an-hour
cut in pay, okay?

52:54.483 --> 52:56.783
My benefits are going down.

52:56.784 --> 52:57.951
I do twice the duties.

52:57.952 --> 53:00.587
I'll be running two plants
instead of one.

53:00.588 --> 53:03.290
If you have $10 million
or if you have $1 billion,

53:03.291 --> 53:07.095
why do you need
that little bit that I have?

53:07.096 --> 53:08.003
Okay?

53:15.003 --> 53:19.439
Big companies are designed
not to generate good jobs

53:19.440 --> 53:21.542
in the United States.

53:21.543 --> 53:25.513
Big companies are designed
to make profits.

53:25.514 --> 53:27.647
And thanks to the members
of the administration,

53:27.648 --> 53:29.450
Jeff and Cass and others
that have worked...

53:29.451 --> 53:31.051
This isn't a matter of fault.

53:31.052 --> 53:32.386
You know, the head of GE

53:32.387 --> 53:34.654
is on the president's
Jobs Council.

53:34.655 --> 53:36.790
I want to start off
by thanking Jeff

53:36.791 --> 53:41.629
for his continued outstanding
leadership of this Jobs Council.

53:41.630 --> 53:44.265
Well, GE has been creating
more jobs abroad

53:44.266 --> 53:47.334
than it's been creating jobs
in the United States.

53:47.335 --> 53:49.971
So who is taking care
of the American worker?

53:49.972 --> 53:52.473
Who is looking out
for the American worker

53:52.474 --> 53:55.908
as GE and other big companies
and Wall Street

53:55.909 --> 53:57.377
and the very wealthy,

53:57.378 --> 53:59.946
who basically have capital
all over the world...

53:59.947 --> 54:03.051
As they have more and more
political power,

54:03.052 --> 54:07.355
who is actually working in a way

54:07.356 --> 54:09.089
in Washington
and in state capitals

54:09.090 --> 54:12.259
that improves the well-being
of the American workforce?

54:12.260 --> 54:14.041
The answer is nobody.

54:27.041 --> 54:30.678
So why didn't the nation respond
to the great regression

54:30.679 --> 54:33.680
that started around 1980?

54:33.681 --> 54:36.584
Why didn't we take bold steps
to make the economy

54:36.585 --> 54:40.824
continue to work
for just about everyone?

54:42.824 --> 54:45.526
Because we figured out
three ways

54:45.527 --> 54:48.462
to cope with flattening
or declining incomes

54:48.463 --> 54:51.668
without reducing our
relative standard of living.

54:53.668 --> 54:57.136
Remember,
starting in the late '70s,

54:57.137 --> 54:59.473
the typical wage is flat.

54:59.474 --> 55:02.009
But a lot of people are buying.

55:02.010 --> 55:04.678
How did they do that?

55:04.679 --> 55:11.417
How does the middle class
manage to keep on spending

55:11.418 --> 55:14.087
when wages are flat?

55:14.088 --> 55:18.026
The first coping mechanism,
starting in the late '70s,

55:18.027 --> 55:23.363
is, women go into paid work.

55:23.364 --> 55:26.366
(BOISTEROUS MUSIC)

55:28.036 --> 55:30.571
 Tumble out of bed
and stumble to the kitchen 

55:30.572 --> 55:32.238
 Pour myself
a cup of ambition 

55:32.239 --> 55:35.642
 And yawn and stretch
and try to come to life 

55:35.643 --> 55:38.745
Young mothers went into
work in huge numbers.

55:38.746 --> 55:40.147
We haven't seen
anything like it,

55:40.148 --> 55:41.348
a social revolution.

55:41.349 --> 55:42.950
 Traffic starts jumpin' 

55:42.951 --> 55:46.319
 With folks like me on the
job from nine to five 

55:46.320 --> 55:48.421
 Working nine to five 

55:48.422 --> 55:49.489
 What a way... 

55:49.490 --> 55:51.892
-<i> Nine to Five.</i>

55:51.893 --> 55:53.194
Dolly Parton?

55:53.195 --> 55:54.995
1980.

55:54.996 --> 55:57.832
Dolly Parton, you know,
she is only five feet tall.

55:57.833 --> 56:00.100
 And they never
give you credit 

56:00.101 --> 56:05.339
 It's enough to drive you
crazy if you let it 

56:05.340 --> 56:06.841
 Nine to five 

56:06.842 --> 56:08.942
They didn't go to work
because there were

56:08.943 --> 56:12.913
all these wonderful professional
opportunities open to women.

56:12.914 --> 56:14.247
Some of them did,

56:14.248 --> 56:16.616
but that's not the major
reason women went to work.

56:16.617 --> 56:19.486
They went to work mainly
because they had to prop up

56:19.487 --> 56:21.122
family incomes
that were dropping

56:21.123 --> 56:22.857
because the men in the family,

56:22.858 --> 56:25.826
their wages were going nowhere.

56:25.827 --> 56:29.196
But there's only a limit
to how many young mothers

56:29.197 --> 56:30.598
can go into work.

56:30.599 --> 56:34.600
And so the second strategy
used by the 1990s

56:34.601 --> 56:38.038
was that families...
both men and women...

56:38.039 --> 56:39.406
worked longer hours.

56:39.407 --> 56:41.741
 Working nine to five 

56:41.742 --> 56:44.210
 What a way to make a living 

56:44.211 --> 56:47.013
 Barely getting by 

56:47.014 --> 56:50.283
When I was secretary of labor,
I remember looking at the data,

56:50.284 --> 56:51.551
and I was amazed,

56:51.552 --> 56:53.287
and then I'd go out
into the field,

56:53.288 --> 56:55.055
and I'd go to various cities,
and I'd talk with people,

56:55.056 --> 56:57.524
and people were working,
you know, all hours...

56:57.525 --> 57:01.629
I mean, second jobs,
third jobs, overtime.

57:01.630 --> 57:02.962
If they were professionals,

57:02.963 --> 57:05.431
billable hours
coming out of their ears.

57:05.432 --> 57:10.236
We were working 300 hours a year
more than the typical European.

57:10.237 --> 57:13.374
I mean, we were working harder
than the industrious...

57:13.375 --> 57:15.408
enormously industrious Japanese.

57:15.409 --> 57:18.444
But there's a limit
to how hard you can work.

57:18.445 --> 57:21.415
When those were exhausted,
the third coping mechanism

57:21.416 --> 57:23.517
was borrowing, going into debt,

57:23.518 --> 57:27.687
which seemed easy because
housing prices were going up.

57:27.688 --> 57:29.256
(SAW BUZZING)

57:29.257 --> 57:32.526
For 13 years, Americans
have enjoyed a housing boom,

57:32.527 --> 57:34.727
the longest ever.

57:34.728 --> 57:37.765
This a great time to buy
a house in Delray Beach.

57:37.766 --> 57:39.633
You can make,
if you have some cash,

57:39.634 --> 57:41.602
an unbelievable deal.

57:41.603 --> 57:45.939
From the mid-to late '90s
onward,

57:45.940 --> 57:48.975
you have this huge rise
in housing prices.

57:48.976 --> 57:51.412
People said, "Well,
I can take out a loan

57:51.413 --> 57:52.712
against my home."

57:52.713 --> 57:54.314
"I could use my home
as collateral,"

57:54.315 --> 57:55.982
or, "I can refinance my home."

57:55.983 --> 57:57.852
And that kept the
middle class going.

57:57.853 --> 57:59.121
Homes were like piggy banks.

58:01.121 --> 58:04.625
Americans have been using
their home as an ATM,

58:04.626 --> 58:09.296
cashing out more than
$500 billion in home equity

58:09.297 --> 58:14.067
from 2001 to 2005 to cover
expenses like health costs,

58:14.068 --> 58:17.474
student debt, repairs,
and credit cards.

58:19.474 --> 58:24.278
We had a debt bubble prompted
by middle-class America

58:24.279 --> 58:27.848
trying to maintain
its living standard

58:27.849 --> 58:30.654
in the face of stagnant wages.

58:32.654 --> 58:35.122
We're seeing more clients
every day that,

58:35.123 --> 58:37.625
very sadly, they've gotten
into a debt hole

58:37.626 --> 58:40.896
that is very difficult
to dig out of.

58:41.896 --> 58:44.096
But there's a limit
to how far you can do that.

58:44.097 --> 58:46.500
You know, that was a
speculative bubble,

58:46.501 --> 58:49.602
and it burst in 2008.

58:49.603 --> 58:50.803
We know what happened.

58:50.804 --> 58:53.306
And so all of the coping
mechanisms

58:53.307 --> 58:59.680
that the middle class has used
to avoid the inevitable reality

58:59.681 --> 59:02.950
that their wages have gone
nowhere for 30 years,

59:02.951 --> 59:07.391
adjusted for inflation,
are now exhausted.

59:10.391 --> 59:14.026
When the middle class doesn't
share in the economic gains,

59:14.027 --> 59:17.132
you get into this downward
vicious cycle.

59:51.132 --> 59:54.701
The problem is,
for the last three decades,

59:54.702 --> 59:57.203
nothing
has fundamentally changed

59:57.204 --> 59:58.612
in terms of inequality.

01:00:00.842 --> 01:00:03.243
And it wasn't until
the Clinton administration

01:00:03.244 --> 01:00:07.080
that there was an opportunity
to reverse all of this.

01:00:07.081 --> 01:00:10.984
And that was what was
so damn frustrating.

01:00:10.985 --> 01:00:13.453
The Senate, I believe,
is on the verge of passing

01:00:13.454 --> 01:00:16.323
the jobs program.

01:00:16.324 --> 01:00:17.491
Things are going well.

01:00:17.492 --> 01:00:20.127
I mean,
we had budget surpluses.

01:00:20.128 --> 01:00:21.995
We might have been able
to take those surpluses

01:00:21.996 --> 01:00:24.397
and invest them in education
and job training,

01:00:24.398 --> 01:00:28.134
change the structure,
ultimately, of the economy.

01:00:28.135 --> 01:00:32.872
But there wasn't the
political will to do that.

01:00:32.873 --> 01:00:34.441
Before I leave,
I also want to say

01:00:34.442 --> 01:00:35.676
a special word of thanks

01:00:35.677 --> 01:00:38.078
to my longtime friend
Secretary Reich,

01:00:38.079 --> 01:00:40.379
who's carried on this fight
for the minimum wage.

01:00:40.380 --> 01:00:42.850
This was an especially
sweet day for him as well,

01:00:42.851 --> 01:00:44.384
and I thank him for his efforts.

01:00:44.385 --> 01:00:49.154
I should say something just
so it's not misunderstood.

01:00:49.155 --> 01:00:52.392
You know,
Bill Clinton did preside

01:00:52.393 --> 01:00:56.263
over one of the best economies
we've had in this country

01:00:56.264 --> 01:00:57.631
in living memory.

01:00:57.632 --> 01:00:59.665
The wages
of most people went up.

01:00:59.666 --> 01:01:02.303
Poverty actually declined.

01:01:02.304 --> 01:01:04.939
But we didn't do enough.

01:01:04.940 --> 01:01:09.614
We did really alter
the underlying trend.

01:01:12.614 --> 01:01:15.515
I became a true pain in the ass.

01:01:15.516 --> 01:01:18.953
I mean, looking back on it,
I'm embarrassed.

01:01:18.954 --> 01:01:21.488
In meetings,
I would sound off about,

01:01:21.489 --> 01:01:23.723
you know, inequality,
and, "Are we looking

01:01:23.724 --> 01:01:27.026
at the distributional impacts
of this policy or that policy?"

01:01:27.027 --> 01:01:28.495
I mean, I became predictable.

01:01:28.496 --> 01:01:30.263
People would roll their eyes.

01:01:30.264 --> 01:01:34.067
I'm surprised Bill Clinton
kept me around.

01:01:34.068 --> 01:01:35.602
I did want to bring you
up to date

01:01:35.603 --> 01:01:37.236
on a couple of matters.

01:01:37.237 --> 01:01:40.339
First of all,
the president was reelected.

01:01:40.340 --> 01:01:42.942
(APPLAUSE)

01:01:42.943 --> 01:01:46.312
The second is that I'm going home.

01:01:46.313 --> 01:01:49.082
(AUDIENCE GROANS)

01:01:49.083 --> 01:01:52.051
(LAUGHTER)

01:01:52.052 --> 01:01:54.288
I am so glad you did not clap.

01:01:54.289 --> 01:01:56.556
(LAUGHTER)

01:01:56.557 --> 01:01:57.823
In the end, I left.

01:01:57.824 --> 01:01:59.491
Partly, I was frustrated.

01:01:59.492 --> 01:02:02.730
Partly, I just hadn't seen
anything in my family.

01:02:02.731 --> 01:02:04.096
I hadn't seen the boys.

01:02:04.097 --> 01:02:07.945
I said to Bill Clinton
I had to go home.

01:02:17.945 --> 01:02:21.814
I... I do ask myself

01:02:21.815 --> 01:02:25.322
whether I've been
a total failure.

01:02:27.322 --> 01:02:31.124
I've been saying much of the
same thing for 30 years.

01:02:31.125 --> 01:02:34.498
And some of the trends
have grown worse.

01:02:36.498 --> 01:02:38.464
Inequality has become worse.

01:02:38.465 --> 01:02:41.271
The danger to the economy and
democracy have become worse.

01:02:44.271 --> 01:02:47.374
But here's what I tell myself

01:02:47.375 --> 01:02:49.375
in my quiet moments.

01:02:49.376 --> 01:02:55.381
I say, close to home,
you know, nuts and bolts,

01:02:55.382 --> 01:02:58.518
over the kitchen sink,
dining room table,

01:02:58.519 --> 01:03:02.087
you know, this is what counts
for most people:

01:03:02.088 --> 01:03:08.062
good jobs, good wages,
a good opportunity

01:03:08.063 --> 01:03:11.665
and set of opportunities
for their kids.

01:03:11.666 --> 01:03:13.036
This is where people live.

01:03:16.036 --> 01:03:18.270
Detective Conan O'Brien

01:03:18.271 --> 01:03:22.246
and Detective Former Secretary
of Labor Robert Reich.

01:03:25.246 --> 01:03:27.080
I am a cockeyed optimist.

01:03:27.081 --> 01:03:29.381
I ask you, do I look
like big government?

01:03:29.382 --> 01:03:30.649
(LAUGHTER)

01:03:30.650 --> 01:03:33.653
I wouldn't have spent
so much of my adult life

01:03:33.654 --> 01:03:36.122
banging my head against the
wall if I didn't think

01:03:36.123 --> 01:03:38.892
that ultimately
it would pay off

01:03:38.893 --> 01:03:41.227
in terms of social change.

01:03:41.228 --> 01:03:44.997
No!

01:03:44.998 --> 01:03:47.404
That's why I teach.

01:03:49.404 --> 01:03:52.339
Now, people who are worried
about widening inequality

01:03:52.340 --> 01:03:56.276
are also worried
about something else.

01:03:56.277 --> 01:03:58.044
It's not upward mobility.

01:03:58.045 --> 01:04:00.046
It's not even trust.

01:04:00.047 --> 01:04:06.556
They are worried about the
undermining of democracy...

01:04:08.556 --> 01:04:12.158
when so many resources,
so much money, so much wealth,

01:04:12.159 --> 01:04:14.794
so much income
accumulates at the very top,

01:04:14.795 --> 01:04:19.598
that with money
comes the capacity

01:04:19.599 --> 01:04:22.938
to control politics.

01:04:23.938 --> 01:04:26.941
(SLICK SPY MUSIC)

01:04:34.581 --> 01:04:36.884
There's nothing sinister
the way it starts.

01:04:36.885 --> 01:04:38.183
Usually they bring in somebody

01:04:38.184 --> 01:04:39.919
you haven't seen
for a few years.

01:04:39.920 --> 01:04:41.888
You know,
they're paying them 10 grand.

01:04:41.889 --> 01:04:43.857
Might be the best man
in your wedding

01:04:43.858 --> 01:04:45.392
or a guy
you played football with.

01:04:45.393 --> 01:04:47.259
You say, "Eddie, hell,
I haven't seen you..."

01:04:47.260 --> 01:04:49.796
And then they say, "Now,
I'd like to turn it over

01:04:49.797 --> 01:04:51.964
to old Freckles here..."

01:04:51.965 --> 01:04:54.701
And then they give you
the whole load.

01:04:54.702 --> 01:04:57.504
But money...
I mean, do the lobbyists come in

01:04:57.505 --> 01:05:02.241
and obviously
the unspoken reality is,

01:05:02.242 --> 01:05:04.009
"We can help you win
your next election

01:05:04.010 --> 01:05:05.312
if you cooperate with us"?

01:05:05.313 --> 01:05:07.448
There's a guy in every office

01:05:07.449 --> 01:05:09.281
to say, "So-and-so
wants to see you.

01:05:09.282 --> 01:05:12.118
"He's from the American
Shoe Leather Company.

01:05:12.119 --> 01:05:14.687
"They have maxed out,"
meaning they gave you

01:05:14.688 --> 01:05:18.125
the maximum in your primary
when you first started.

01:05:18.126 --> 01:05:20.326
"They gave you the maximum
in every general.

01:05:20.327 --> 01:05:21.962
"You've run three times now,

01:05:21.963 --> 01:05:24.730
and they were there for you
at every point."

01:05:24.731 --> 01:05:25.966
And what for?

01:05:25.967 --> 01:05:27.670
Access.

01:05:29.670 --> 01:05:31.904
This is actually
where there is blame,

01:05:31.905 --> 01:05:35.008
and I think the blame
is justifiable.

01:05:35.009 --> 01:05:36.475
It's not that people are rich.

01:05:36.476 --> 01:05:40.279
It's that they abuse
their wealth

01:05:40.280 --> 01:05:46.720
by lobbying for bailouts
and subsidies and taxes

01:05:46.721 --> 01:05:49.756
that are going to entrench
their wealth.

01:05:49.757 --> 01:05:53.593
That's the reason why the rules
have changed so dramatically.

01:05:53.594 --> 01:05:54.895
Look at history.

01:05:54.896 --> 01:05:57.430
Inequality and top tax rates

01:05:57.431 --> 01:05:59.899
have had
an inverse relationship.

01:05:59.900 --> 01:06:03.669
When inequality was lowest,
top tax rates were higher.

01:06:03.670 --> 01:06:07.439
When inequality was highest,
tax rates on the wealthy

01:06:07.440 --> 01:06:08.753
went down.

01:06:19.753 --> 01:06:23.089
Under Dwight D. Eisenhower...
you know, he was a Republican;

01:06:23.090 --> 01:06:25.058
nobody dared call him
a socialist...

01:06:25.059 --> 01:06:29.395
the top marginal tax rate
was 91%.

01:06:29.396 --> 01:06:30.997
I mean, even when you consider

01:06:30.998 --> 01:06:33.100
all deductions
and all tax credits,

01:06:33.101 --> 01:06:35.602
they were still paying
way over 50%.

01:06:35.603 --> 01:06:38.705
I, John Fitzgerald Kennedy,
do solemnly swear...

01:06:38.706 --> 01:06:40.306
I will faithfully execute...

01:06:40.307 --> 01:06:43.709
The office of president
of the United States...

01:06:43.710 --> 01:06:44.877
So help me, God.

01:06:44.878 --> 01:06:46.178
So help me, God.

01:06:46.179 --> 01:06:50.484
Taxes on the top
were never below 70%

01:06:50.485 --> 01:06:54.126
until Reagan dropped
those taxes on the top.

01:06:59.126 --> 01:07:01.694
Read my lips.

01:07:01.695 --> 01:07:05.098
No new taxes.

01:07:05.099 --> 01:07:07.968
I, William Jefferson Clinton...

01:07:07.969 --> 01:07:09.134
I, George Walker Bush...

01:07:09.135 --> 01:07:10.335
Do solemnly swear...

